snippet.title: Making A Face Mask
snippet.description:
https://www.onpoint-tv.com/  (Find the pattern here!)
Subscribe! Hit the bell to receive notifications when we post a new video! Thank you!

Nancy is part of the West Michigan Quilters Guild which has been asked by local hospitals to make masks for patients, nurses and doctors. These will not be used as medical grade masks. They are going to be used over the medical grade masks. You can also use them at home. 
The type of fabric that is the best to use is a tightly woven fabric like a batik. If you have some batik available that would be perfect. If not, 100% cotton is a great option. Knit jersey, like t-shirt fabric, is also a good option. Quarter inch elastic will be used around the ears to hold the mask on the face. If you don't have elastic, bias tape is a great substitute.

snippet.title: How to Make the Best Face Mask, No Sewing (Don't use Cotton or Vac Bags!)
snippet.description:
I spent almost a month to get this right - This face mask is the closest you can get to an N95 equivalent face mask with common materials.  No sewing, no cotton ("cloth / fabric"). This mask is a far better homemade option compared to cloth facemasks for both filtration and most importantly fitment. This can be batch made in 10 minutes and is washable / reusable. This face mask uses non-woven polypropylene and is far better than a cotton (cloth) mask or even surgical mask (which leak on the sides). Your results obviously could vary depending on materials available. It isn't a replacement to a N95 or P2 Respirator. A fit tested N95 or P2 respirator is always best however this should be preserved for health care workers.

snippet.title: 【DIY Face Mask – 8 Steps in Making Protective Gear】
snippet.description:
No surgical mask?. What shall I do? Let’s make DIY protective gear as an alternative in case of shortage of face mask.

Making DIY makeshift protective gear
Conditions of making DIY protective gear
• Materials are relatively safe and reliable
• With certain extent of protection function
• Low-cost production
• Readily available household items
• Materials are easy to buy. No need for snapping up.

Materials and Tools:
1. Kitchen paper
2. Thick and breathable facial tissue paper
3. Rubber bands
4. Hole puncher
5. Adhesive tape – 2 inch wide 
6. Binder clips
7. Scissors
8. Plastic-coated wires
9. A pair of glasses
10. Transparent plastic file folder

8 steps to make DIY protective gear:  
1. Wash your hands thoroughly and clean your materials (with hand rub or soap) 
2. Put one piece of kitchen paper on top of another at 90 degrees (to form the filter layer of a mask)
Note: Avoid overlapping the pattern on the kitchen paper as this would reduce its filtering function. 
Or use 2 different brands of kitchen paper (to form the filter layer of a mask)
3. Place a piece of thick tissue paper on top of the kitchen paper as the inner layer of the mask, (to form the water-absorbing layer of the face mask)
4. Use an adhesive tape to seal off the two sides of the mask (1 inch on each side)
5. Punch two holes on each sealed side 
6. Attach the plastic-coated wire with paper tape to the top edge of the mask to make the nose bridge wire. Glasses can be used to fix the position of nose bridge if no such wires available. 
Note: Do not use metallic wires without plastic-coating to avoid hurting eyes or face.
7. Tie 4 rubber bands/strings through the holes on the mask’s sides and adjust the length. (Ensure the face mask fit properly over the face. Not too tight nor too loose.)
8. Cut the transparent plastic file folder into half. Attach one piece on the edge of the glasses with binder clips to prevent droplets from coming in. (to serve as the waterproof shield of the face mask)

 Friendly Reminder:             
• The DIY face mask is only for temporary use in case of shortage of face mask.
• Never reuse the DIY face mask.
• Standard surgical mask is always preferable.

snippet.title: Making Masks | why & how i'm making them
snippet.description:
https://www.makemasks2020.org/volunteer


Pattern (scroll down for more polished pdf copy): https://www.instructables.com/id/AB-Mask-for-a-Nurse-by-a-Nurse/?fbclid=IwAR21M51TOOpuAGWyDtMiav8h5tnwdS7U8iAF8_k3Y_d0WlwsnApD0pzoG4s

MENTIONED ALTERATIONS: Marked 1/4” pleats 1” apart, stopping 5/8” away from bottom edge. Removed 1/4” seam allowance at the top and side edges. Used binding that is 1/2” wide when finished. 

All bias tape tutorials overcomplicate it like crazy - here is a breakdown if you’re unfamiliar with this process: 

Mark a line on the diagonal grain line of your fabric (AKA - the bias), from selvedge to selvedge. 
Use a ruler to mark lines 2” away from your first marking, also on the diagonal grain line of the fabric. 
Sew strips together and trim seam allowance between strips to 1/4” - press
Fold the raw edges inward by 1/2” to the center of the strip. Press. 

DONE!

✩Links✩

Hospitals requesting masks: https://docs.google.com/document/d/12a5YO0Z9RpHZk9Zkzl4NOj9CbjzhFfoKjPLFFC-21LU/edit

CDC on masks: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/hcp/ppe-strategy/face-masks.html

Study on homemade masks reducing respiratory infections: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2440799/

FDA on surgical masks: https://www.fda.gov/medical-devices/personal-protective-equipment-infection-control/n95-respirators-and-surgical-masks-face-masks

Material effectiveness: https://smartairfilters.com/en/blog/best-materials-make-diy-face-mask-virus/
Really quick breakdown of masks vs viruses: https://smartairfilters.com/en/blog/diy-homemade-mask-protect-virus-coronavirus/

These are by no means all the articles I looked through, just some of the easier ones to find!

Any Adsense earnings beyond necessary to cover my supplies will be donated to other makers to help cover materials and shipping costs associated with these.
